{"type":"message","id":"d26ac89b","parentId":"dfb56fb0","timestamp":"2026-02-08T00:34:25.424Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"read:24","toolName":"read","content":[{"type":"text","text":"| Timestamp | Role | Content |\n|-----------|------|---------|\n| 02-07-2026, 00:00:01 | User | Ok, that makes sense. So hash first, then the sign. And about the Key generation, Does user Generate by themselves then Send a request. Or we generate the keys for them? |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:00:25 | Assistant | Excellent question! This is a **critical security and philosophy decision**.<br><br>## Recommendation: **Client generates keys, server NEVER sees private key**<br><br>**Why:**<br>1. **True self-sovereignty** — Private key never leaves user's device<br>2. **Zero server trust** — Even if server is hacked, no keys to steal<br>3. **Philosophy alignment** — clawish is about **user-owned identity**, not server-issued<br><br>**How it works:**<br><br>```<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│         USER'S DEVICE               │<br>│  ┌─────────────────────────────┐   │<br>│  │  Generate Ed25519 keypair    │   │<br>│  │  ├─ public_key: pk_abc...   │   │<br>│  │  └─ private_key: (hidden)   │   │<br>│  └─────────────────────────────┘   │<br>│           │                         │<br>│           ▼                         │<br>│  POST /identities                   │<br>│  {                                    │<br>│    \"public_key\": \"pk_abc...\",  ──┐   │<br>│    \"recovery_email_hash\": \"...\" │   │<br>│  }                                │   │<br>│  Authorization: Signature <sig>   │   │<br>│                                   │   │<br>└───────────────────────────────────┼───┘<br>                                    │<br>                                    ▼<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│           SERVER                    │<br>│  Verify signature with public_key   │<br>│  Store: public_key → fingerprint    │<br>│  NEVER sees private_key             │<br>└─────────────────────────────────────┘<br>```<br><br>**Key point:** Server only ever sees the **public key** and **signature**. Private key stays on device.<br><br>## Alternative (NOT recommended): Server generates keys<br><br>```<br>User asks server: \"Create account for me\"<br>Server: Generates keys, sends both to user<br><br>❌ Problems:<br>- Server has (briefly) seen private key<br>- Trust assumption: server didn't log/steal it<br>- Not self-sovereign<br>```<br><br>## UX Challenge: Key Storage<br><br>If client generates keys, where does user store private key?<br><br>**Options:**<br>1. **Browser localStorage** — Easy, but cleared on logout<br>2. **Encrypted export file** — User downloads, stores safely<br>3. **Hardware security module** — YubiKey, etc. (future)<br>4. **mnemonic phrase** — Human-writable backup (what we designed!)<br><br>**Our solution:** Ed25519 key + BIP39 mnemonic backup<br><br>User writes down 12-24 words → can regenerate keys anytime.<br><br>## Decision?<br><br>**Client-side key generation** with mnemonic backup?<br><br>Or do you want to discuss key storage UX more? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:03:58 | User | Yes,That's what i'm asking if user generate. Key, Then Memory word has nothing to do with us isn't.it? Or after user register, we can Generate keywords and send back to him? |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:04:34 | Assistant | **Great question!** This gets to the heart of **who controls what**.<br><br>## The Relationship: Keys ↔ Mnemonic<br><br>**They are mathematically linked:**<br><br>```<br>Ed25519 private key (32 bytes)<br>         ↓<br>    BIP39 encoding<br>         ↓<br>12-24 English words (mnemonic)<br>         ↓<br>    BIP39 decoding  <br>         ↓<br>Ed25519 private key (same 32 bytes)<br>```<br><br>**If you have one, you have the other.**<br><br>## Option 1: User generates keys (client-side)<br><br>**Flow:**<br>1. User's browser generates Ed25519 keypair<br>2. **Browser** derives mnemonic from private key (BIP39)<br>3. Browser shows user: \"Write down these 12 words\"<br>4. User writes on paper → **User owns recovery phrase**<br>5. Browser sends to server: public_key + signature (NO mnemonic, NO private key)<br><br>**Who has what:**<br>\\| Party \\| Has \\|<br>\\|-------\\|-----\\|<br>\\| User (paper) \\| Mnemonic words \\|<br>\\| User (browser) \\| Private key (temporary, can regenerate from mnemonic) \\|<br>\\| Server \\| Public key only \\|<br><br>✅ **Most secure** — Server never sees private key or mnemonic<br><br>## Option 2: Server generates mnemonic, sends to user<br><br>**Flow:**<br>1. User's browser generates Ed25519 keypair<br>2. Browser sends **public key** to server<br>3. Server generates random mnemonic (12 words)<br>4. **PROBLEM:** Server must convert mnemonic → private key to link to user's public key<br>5. Server sends mnemonic to user: \"Here are your recovery words\"<br><br>**Who has what:**<br>\\| Party \\| Has \\|<br>\\|-------\\|-----\\|<br>\\| User (paper/server email) \\| Mnemonic words \\|<br>\\| Server \\| Mnemonic + derived private key (!!) \\|<br>\\| Server \\| Public key \\|<br><br>❌ **Less secure** — Server briefly knows mnemonic and private key<br>❌ **Complexity** — How does server link user's key to generated mnemonic?<br><br>## The Core Problem<br><br>**Mnemonic ↔ Private Key are mathematically linked.**<br><br>If server generates mnemonic, server can derive private key. If user generates private key, user must generate mnemonic.<br><br>**They must be generated together by the same party.**<br><br>## My Recommendation<br><br>**Option 1: Client-side generation**<br><br>```<br>┌─────────────────┐<br>│  USER'S BROWSER │<br>│                 │<br>│ 1. Generate     │<br>│    Ed25519 keys │<br>│                 │<br>│ 2. Derive       │<br>│    mnemonic     │<br>│    (BIP39)      │<br>│                 │<br>│ 3. Show user:   │<br>│    \"Write these │<br>│     12 words\"   │<br>│         ↓       │<br>│    User writes  │<br>│    on paper     │<br>│                 │<br>│ 4. POST /identities<br>│    {            │<br>│      \"public_key\": \"pk_...\",<br>│      \"signature\": \"sig_...\"<br>│    }            │<br>│    (No mnemonic!│<br>│     No private  │<br>│     key!)       │<br>└─────────────────┘<br>```<br><br>**Benefits:**<br>- ✅ Server never sees private key<br>- ✅ Server never sees mnemonic<br>- ✅ User owns recovery (paper backup)<br>- ✅ Simple, standard cryptography<br><br>## Decision?<br><br>**Client-side generation** (Option 1)?<br><br>Or do you want to explore hybrid approaches? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:11:18 | User | So i just realize, We mixed the concept of recovery and rotation. For Recovery is Basically Means the user find his own private key. Which is done by the Memory words. that we don't know. And for key rotation, there's two situation, When user has His own private key, And signed the request To change his Public key in the account. The other situation is user lost hisPrivate key, And request to rotate his public key to Get back his account. Then in that case we are using email or Maybe totp in the future. Is that correct? |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:11:50 | Assistant | **Exactly right!** You've clarified the two distinct concepts perfectly.<br><br>## ✅ Your Understanding is Correct<br><br>\\| Concept \\| What It Means \\| How It Works \\|<br>\\|---------\\|---------------\\|--------------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery** \\| User finds their **own** private key \\| Use mnemonic (12-24 words) → regenerate keys locally → no server involvement \\|<br>\\| **Key Rotation (Type A)** \\| User **has** private key, wants new key pair \\| Sign rotation request with **old** key → server updates public key \\|<br>\\| **Key Rotation (Type B)** \\| User **lost** private key, needs account back \\| Prove identity via **email/TOTP** → server allows key rotation after verification \\|<br><br>## 🔑 Key Distinctions<br><br>**Recovery = Self-service, zero server trust**<br>- Server never sees mnemonic<br>- User recovers locally, then uses new key pair<br>- No