tions** section distinguishing Recovery vs Key Rotation<br>- Three distinct concepts: Recovery (self-service), Rotation Type A (has old key), Rotation Type B (lost key)<br><br>**In `verification-recovery-methods.md`:**<br>- Added **Core Concepts** section at the top<br>- Clarified that \"Recovery\" = user regenerates their own key (zero server trust)<br>- Key Rotation = server-coordinated key replacement (with or without old key)<br><br>**The key insight you identified:**<br>- **Recovery** = Client-side mnemonic → same key (no server)<br>- **Rotation Type A** = Sign with old key → new key (server verifies)<br>- **Rotation Type B** = Email/TOTP proof → new key (server validates + delay)<br><br>This makes the security model clear:<br>- Most secure (Recovery): Zero server trust, happens offline<br>- Medium secure (Rotation A): Cryptographic proof, immediate<br>- Least secure (Rotation B): Trust-based, time-delayed<br><br>Should I now commit these documentation updates? And then we can continue with the next open question from need-discuss.md? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:40:14 | User | So for the users Memory words and self service we don't need to. code anything? Just need to write the documentation for them right? So the AI will do by themselves? |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:40:49 | Assistant | Exactly right! **For mnemonic-based recovery, we code almost nothing on the server.**<br><br>## What We Code vs Document<br><br>\\| Component \\| Server Code \\| Client Code \\| Documentation \\|<br>\\|-----------\\|-------------\\|-------------\\|---------------\\|<br>\\| **Mnemonic generation** \\| ❌ None \\| ✅ BIP39 library \\| ✅ How to use \\|<br>\\| **Key derivation** (mnemonic → seed → Ed25519) \\| ❌ None \\| ✅ Crypto library \\| ✅ BIP39 + Ed25519 flow \\|<br>\\| **Signature verification** \\| ✅ Already doing \\| ❌ None \\| ✅ API spec \\|<br>\\| **Key rotation** (updating public key) \\| ✅ Type A/B handling \\| ✅ Sign with old key \\| ✅ Flow documentation \\|<br><br>## Server's Perspective<br><br>From the server's view, **there is no \"recovery\" endpoint for mnemonics**:<br><br>```<br>Normal Login:<br>POST /auth/challenge<br>← Returns: { challenge: \"random_string\" }<br><br>POST /auth/verify<br>Body: {<br>  \"public_key\": \"pk_abc123...\",  // Server looks this up<br>  \"signature\": \"sig_xyz...\"       // Server verifies<br>}<br>← Returns: { token: \"jwt_token\" }<br><br>Server thinks: \"This signature matches public_key. Authenticated!\"<br>```<br><br>After \"recovery\" (user regenerated key from mnemonic):<br>```<br>POST /auth/verify<br>Body: {<br>  \"public_key\": \"pk_abc123...\",  // SAME public key as before!<br>  \"signature\": \"sig_xyz...\"<br>}<br>← Returns: { token: \"jwt_token\" }<br><br>Server thinks: \"Same as always. This signature matches. Authenticated!\"<br>```<br><br>**Server cannot tell if user:**<br>- Never lost their key (normal use)<br>- Recovered from mnemonic 5 minutes ago<br>- Is a different AI with the same key (impossible — Ed25519 keys are unique)<br><br>## What We Actually Code<br><br>**Server:**<br>- Ed25519 signature verification (already doing)<br>- Key rotation endpoints (Type A and Type B)<br>- Standard auth flow (challenge/verify)<br><br>**Client (Browser/App/AI):**<br>- BIP39 mnemonic generation (12-24 words)<br>- BIP39 → seed → Ed25519 key derivation<br>- LocalStorage or secure storage for private key<br>- UI: \"Write down these words!\" prompt<br><br>**Documentation:**<br>- BIP39 word list standard<br>- Ed25519 key derivation path<br>- Security best practices (paper backup, never share mnemonic)<br><br>## The Code That Doesn't Exist<br><br>```<br>❌ POST /recovery/mnemonic   ← Doesn't exist!<br>❌ POST /account/recover    ← Doesn't exist!<br>❌ Server mnemonic storage  ← Never happens!<br>```<br><br>Instead:<br>```<br>✅ Client: bip39.generateMnemonic()  // Local only<br>✅ Client: bip39.mnemonicToSeed()     // Local only  <br>✅ Client: ed25519.fromSeed()          // Local only<br>✅ Client: POST /auth/verify (same as normal!)<br>```<br><br>## Summary<br><br>\\| Question \\| Answer \\|<br>\\|----------\\|--------\\|<br>\\| Do we code server \"recovery\" for mnemonics? \\| ❌ No \\|<br>\\| Do we code client mnemonic → key generation? \\| ✅ Yes (BIP39 + Ed25519 libraries) \\|<br>\\| Do we document the flow? \\| ✅ Yes (user writes down words, regenerates key) \\|<br>\\| Does server know if user \"recovered\"? \\| ❌ No — same public key, same signature flow \\|<br><br>**The beauty:** Mnemonic recovery is **invisible** to the server. It's purely client-side. The server just sees \"valid signature from known public key\" — whether that's day 1 or day 1000 after recovery.<br><br>Does this clarify? The \"code\" is just using existing BIP39 and Ed25519 libraries in the client! 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:42:13 | User | So one good thing about our design is even if user lost his private key or the memory words. he still has Method to Get back his account, Which is to rotate the key. |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:42:32 | Assistant | Exactly! That's a **key design benefit** of the three-layer approach:<br><br>## The Safety Net Layers<br><br>\\| Layer \\| Scenario \\| Method \\| Server Trust \\|<br>\\|-------\\|----------\\|--------\\|--------------\\|<br>\\| **1. Self-Service** \\| Lost key, **have mnemonic** \\| Recovery (regenerate same key) \\| **Zero** \\|<br>\\| **2. Cryptographic** \\| Lost key, **have old key** \\| Rotation Type A (sign with old key) \\| Verify signature \\|<br>\\| **3. Trust-Based** \\| **Lost everything** (no mnemonic, no key) \\| Rotation Type B (email/TOTP) \\| Validate + time delay \\|<br><br>## The Key Insight<br><br>**Even in the worst case** — fire destroyed your house, you lost your phone, forgot your mnemonic, and have no backup keys — **you can still get your account back** through Type B rotation.<br><br>**The trade-off:** Time delay (24-48 hours) + lower security (trust-based, not cryptographic).<br><br>**But:** You don't lose your identity, your history, or your