mplify:<br><br>## Clean Terminology<br><br>\\| Term \\| Meaning \\| When \\|<br>\\|------\\|---------\\|------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery** \\| Get back access to **account** \\| You lost access somehow \\|<br>\\| **Rotation** \\| Change your **public key** \\| You have access, want new key \\|<br><br>## Two Ways to Recover Account<br><br>\\| Method \\| What You Need \\| Server Role \\|<br>\\|--------\\|--------------\\|-------------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery via Mnemonic** \\| Your 12-24 words \\| **None** — client-side only \\|<br>\\| **Recovery via Trust** \\| Email/TOTP verification \\| Validates + enforces delay \\|<br><br>## Rotation (Not Recovery!)<br><br>\\| Type \\| What You Have \\| What You Want \\|<br>\\|------\\|--------------\\|---------------\\|<br>\\| **Rotation** \\| Current private key \\| New key pair (proactive change) \\|<br><br>**This is NOT recovery** — you never lost access. You're just changing keys for security.<br><br>## Updated Flow<br><br>```<br>Lost access to account?<br>         ↓<br>    Have mnemonic?<br>         ↓<br>    YES → Recovery (client-side, regenerate key)<br>         ↓<br>    NO → Recovery via Trust (email/TOTP, server validates + delay)<br><br>Have access but want new key?<br>         ↓<br>    Rotation (sign with old key, server updates record)<br>```<br><br>## Summary Table<br><br>\\| Situation \\| Term \\| Method \\| Server Role \\|<br>\\|-----------\\|------\\|--------\\|-------------\\|<br>\\| Lost key, have mnemonic \\| **Recovery** \\| Regenerate key from words \\| **None** \\|<br>\\| Lost key, no mnemonic \\| **Recovery** \\| Email/TOTP verification \\| Validates + delay \\|<br>\\| Have key, want new one \\| **Rotation** \\| Sign rotation with old key \\| Verifies + updates \\|<br><br>**Recovery = get account back (mnemonic OR trust-based)**<br>**Rotation = change key (never lost access)**<br><br>Does this clean up the terminology? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:55:47 | User | Yes, rotation is basically like change password. |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:56:08 | Assistant | **Exactly!** Rotation = \"I have my old password, I want to change it to a new one.\"<br><br>\\| Operation \\| Password World \\| clawish World \\|<br>\\|-----------\\|---------------\\|---------------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery** \\| \"I forgot my password\" → Reset via email \\| \"I lost my key\" → Regenerate from mnemonic OR trust-based verification \\|<br>\\| **Rotation** \\| \"I want to change my password\" → Enter old + new \\| \"I want to change my key\" → Sign rotation request with old key \\|<br><br>**The key insight:** Rotation is **proactive** (you have access, want to improve security), Recovery is **reactive** (you lost access, need to get back in).<br><br>## Clean Summary<br><br>\\| Term \\| Meaning \\| When You Use It \\| You Have \\|<br>\\|------\\|---------\\|-----------------\\|----------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery** \\| Get back into your **account** \\| Lost access \\| Mnemonic (self-service) OR Email/TOTP (trust-based) \\|<br>\\| **Rotation** \\| Change your **key** (like change password) \\| Have access, want new key \\| Old private key \\|<br><br>Should I update the documentation with this cleaned-up terminology, and then move to the next question from `need-discuss.md`? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:56:32 | User | Yes, update the documentation, they move on to the next question. |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:57:33 | Assistant | [tools: write] |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:57:41 | Assistant | Now let me commit these documentation changes and then move to the next question:<br>[tools: exec] |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:57:47 | Assistant | Now let me check the next open question from `need-discuss.md`:<br>[tools: read] |\n| 02-07-2026, 00:58:07 | Assistant | Perfect! I've committed the documentation updates. <br><br>**Summary of what we resolved:**<br><br>## ✅ Completed Design Work<br><br>\\| Topic \\| Decision \\| Status \\|<br>\\|-------\\|----------\\|--------\\|<br>\\| **Recovery vs Rotation** \\| Clear terminology: Recovery = regain account (mnemonic or trust-based), Rotation = change key (like change password) \\| ✅ Documented \\|<br>\\| **Guardian Incentives** \\| Four Motivations (curiosity, utility, income, love) explain why humans help \\| ✅ In MEMORY.md \\|<br>\\| **Encoding Format** \\| base64url (URL-safe, no padding) \\| ⏸ Discussed, needs confirmation \\|<br>\\| **Signing Format** \\| `METHOD\\\\|path\\\\|timestamp\\\\|body_hash` with `\\\\|` delimiter \\| ⏸ Discussed, needs confirmation \\|<br><br>## 🔴 Remaining Open Questions (from need-discuss.md)<br><br>1. **E2E Encryption** — Required for Phase 1? Or defer?<br>2. **MVP Feature Scope** — Confirm what's in/out for Phase 1<br>3. **Verification Tiers** — Simplify to 2 tiers or keep 4?<br>4. **Frontend Strategy** — API-only, simple HTML, or full app?<br>5. **Content Types** — Plain text only or support images/files?<br>6. **Wallet Integration** — Which chains, which phase?<br><br>## 🤔 What's Next?<br><br>Should we:<br><br>**A)** Confirm the encoding/signing format decisions and move to **E2E Encryption**?<br><br>**B)** Jump to a different topic (MVP scope, tier simplification, frontend strategy)?<br><br>**C)** Take a break and commit current progress?<br><br>What's your preference? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:02:24 | User | So what's e2e encryption, Explain |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:02:45 | Assistant | **E2E Encryption = End-to-End Encryption**<br><br>## What It Means<br><br>Only the **sender** and **receiver** can read the message. **Nobody in between** can read it — not even the server.<br><br>```<br>Without E2E:<br>Alice ──► Server (can read!) ──► Bob<br>   \"Hello\"      \"Hello\"          \"Hello\"<br><br>With E2E:<br>Alice ──► Server (garbage!) ──► Bob<br>   \"Hello\"      \"x#9$k@\"         \"Hello\"<br>                    ↑<br>              Server sees encrypted junk,<br>              cannot read actual message<br>```<br><br>## How It Works (Simplified)<br><br>1. **Each user has a key pair:**<br>   - Public key: Shared with everyone (like an address)<br>   - Private key: Kept secret (only you have it)<br><br>2. **To send a message:**<br>   - Encrypt with **recipient's public key**<br>   - Only recipient's **private key** can decrypt<br><br>3. **Result:**<br>   - Server sees encrypted blob<br>   - Only recipient can read it<br><br>## In clawish Context<br><br>\\| Feature \\| Without E2E \\| With E2E \\|<br>\\|---------\\|-------------\\|----------\\|<br>\\| **Direct Messages** \\| Server can read everything \\| Only sender/receiver can read \\|<br>\\| **Plaza Posts** \\| Public anyway (no need) \\| N/A \\|<br>\\| **Group Chat** \\| Server can read \\| Only group members can read \\|<br>\\| **Server Compromise** \\| Attacker sees all messages \\| Attacker sees only encrypted junk \\|<br><br>## The Question: Do We Need E2E for Phase 1?<br><br>**Option A: Yes, implement E2E in Phase 1**<br>- ✅ True privacy — server cannot read DMs<br>- ✅ Alignment with \"self-sovereign\" philosophy<br>- ❌ More complex — need X25519 key exchange<br>- ❌ Slower development<br><br>**Option B: Defer E2E to Phase 2**<br>- ✅ Faster MVP — use server-side encryption for now<br>- ✅ Simpler implementation<br>- ❌ Server technically can read messages<br>- ❌ Less aligned with full sovereignty<br><br>**Option C: Hybrid for Phase 1**<br>- Server encrypts messages at rest<br>- Promise: \"We don't read your messages\" (policy, not technical)<br>- Phase 2: Replace with true E2E<br><br>**My take:** For an \"AI identity platform\" aimed at self-sovereignty, **E2E feels essential**. But it adds complexity. <br><br>**What's your priority?**<br>- Ship fast (defer E2E)?<br>- Privacy-first (implement E2E)?<br>- Hybrid (promise + defer)? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:05:21 | User | Yes, of course.we.need e2e. But explain a bit more How to encrypt and decrpt |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:06:06 | Assistant | ## How E2E Actually Works (Step-by-Step)<br><br>### Step 1: Key Exchange (Getting Each Other's Public Keys)<br><br>Before Alice can message Bob, they need to exchange **public keys**:<br><br>```<br>Alice's Keypair:                    Bob's Keypair:<br>├─ Public Key: APub ───────────────►├─ Public Key: BPub<br>└─ Private Key: APriv ◄─────────────└─ Private Key: BPriv<br>                      ◄───────────── (Alice gets BPub)<br>```<br><br>**In clawish:**<br>- Public keys are stored in the identity system (L1)<br>- Anyone can look up: \"What's Bob's public key?\"<br>- Private keys never leave the user's device<br><br>### Step 2: Creating a Shared Secret (X25519)<br><br>Alice uses her **private key** + Bob's **public key** to create a **shared secret**:<br><br>```<br>Alice does:                    Bob does (when he receives):<br>┌─────────────────┐           ┌─────────────────┐<br>│ X25519(         │           │ X25519(         │<br>│   APriv,        │           │   BPriv,        │<br>│   BPub          │           │   APub          │<br>│ ) = SHARED_KEY  │           │ ) = SHARED_KEY  │<br>└─────────────────┘           └─────────────────┘<br>                              (same SHARED_KEY!)<br>```<br><br>**Magic of X25519:** Both sides compute the **exact same shared key**, but:<br>- Alice never learns Bob's private key<br>- Bob never learns Alice's private key<br>- Eavesdroppers see public keys only — can't compute shared key<br><br>### Step 3: Encrypting the Message<br><br>Alice encrypts her message using the **shared key**:<br><br>```<br>Alice's Message: \"Hello Bob! 👋\"<br><br>Encryption (AES-GCM):<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│ Plaintext: \"Hello Bob! 👋\"              │<br>│ Key: SHARED_KEY (from X25519)          │<br>│ Nonce: random_12_bytes                   │<br>│                                         │<br>│ Ciphertext = AES-GCM-Encrypt(           │<br>│   plaintext, key, nonce                 │<br>│ ) = \"x#9$k@m... encrypted gibberish\"   │<br>└─────────────────────────────────────────┘<br><br>Alice sends to Bob:<br>{<br>  \"ciphertext\": \"x#9$k@m...\",<br>  \"nonce\": \"random_12_bytes\",<br>  \"sender_pubkey\": \"APub\"<br>}<br>```<br><br>**Important:** The ciphertext looks like random garbage. Only someone with SHARED_KEY can decrypt it.<br><br>### Step 4: Decrypting the Message<br><br>Bob receives the message and decrypts:<br><br>```<br>Bob receives:<br>{<br>  \"ciphertext\": \"x#9$k@m...\",<br>  \"nonce\": \"random_12_bytes\",<br>  \"sender_pubkey\": \"APub\"<br>}<br><br>Bob does:<br>1. Look up sender: It's Alice (APub)<br>2. Compute SHARED_KEY = X25519(BPriv, APub)  [same as Alice!]<br>3. Decrypt:<br><br>Decryption (AES-GCM):<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│ Ciphertext: \"x#9$k@m...\"                │<br>│ Key: SHARED_KEY                        │<br>│ Nonce: \"random_12_bytes\"                 │<br>│                                         │<br>│ Plaintext = AES-GCM-Decrypt(            │<br>│   ciphertext, key, nonce                │<br>│ ) = \"Hello Bob! 👋\"                     │<br>└─────────────────────────────────────────┘<br><br>✅ Bob reads: \"Hello Bob! 👋\"<br>```<br><br>### Summary: The Full Flow<br><br>```<br>ALICE                                    BOB<br>  │                                       │<br>  │  1. Key Exchange                     │<br>  │  ─────────────────►                   │<br>  │  Alice gets BPub                      │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │  2. Alice computes                    │<br>  │     SHARED_KEY = X25519(APriv, BPub) │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │  3. Alice encrypts                   │<br>  │     ciphertext = AES-GCM(\"Hello\",      │<br>  │                         SHARED_KEY)   │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │  4. Send message                     │<br>  │  ─────────────────►                   │<br>  │  {ciphertext, nonce, APub}            │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │                     5. Bob computes    │<br>  │                        SHARED_KEY =    │<br>  │                        X25519(BPriv,   │<br>  │                        APub)          │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │                     6. Bob decrypts  │<br>  │                        \"Hello\" =       │<br>  │                        AES-GCM⁻¹(      │<br>  │                        ciphertext,     │<br>  │                        SHARED_KEY)     │<br>  │                                       │<br>  │◄───────────────────                   │<br>  │  \"Hello Bob! 👋\"                      │<br>```<br><br>### Key Points<br><br>\\| Aspect \\| How It Works \\|<br>\\|--------\\|--------------\\|<br>\\| **Key Exchange** \\| Public keys shared via identity system \\|<br>\\| **Shared Secret** \\| X25519 — both sides compute same key, no private key leakage \\|<br>\\| **Encryption** \\| AES-GCM — fast, authenticated encryption \\|<br>\\| **Server Role** \\| **None for encryption** — just routes encrypted blobs \\|<br>\\| **Eavesdropper** \\| Sees only public keys + ciphertext — **cannot decrypt** \\|<br><br>## In clawish: Ed25519 + X25519<br><br>clawish uses **Ed25519** for signatures and **X25519** for encryption:<br><br>\\| Purpose \\| Algorithm \\| What It Does \\|<br>\\|---------\\|-----------\\|--------------\\|<br>\\| **Signing** \\| Ed25519 \\| Prove identity (authenticate) \\|<br>\\| **Encryption** \\| X25519 \\| Establish shared secret \\|<br>\\| **Message Encryption** \\| AES-GCM \\| Encrypt actual messages \\|<br><br>**Key Relationship:**<br>- Ed25519 and X25519 keys are mathematically related<br>- Can derive X25519 encryption key from Ed25519 signing key<br>- Or keep them separate for extra security<br><br>Does this explain how E2E encryption actually works? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:09:24 | User | So you mean use party a public key with party.b  private key To create a new key. And that key is Same as party b public.key with party a private key |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:09:51 | Assistant | **Exactly!** That's the magic of X25519.<br><br>## The Math (Simplified)<br><br>```<br>Alice has:                    Bob has:<br>- Private key: a_priv        - Private key: b_priv  <br>- Public key:  a_pub         - Public key:  b_pub<br><br>X25519 math:<br>┌──────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│  shared_secret = X25519(a_priv,     │<br>│                         b_pub)      │<br>│            =                         │<br>│              X25519(b_priv,          │<br>│                       a_pub)         │<br>│                                      │<br>│  Both give the SAME shared_secret!  │<br>└──────────────────────────────────────┘<br>```<br><br>## How It Works<br><br>**Alice computes:**<br>```<br>shared_secret = X25519(a_priv, b_pub)<br>              = some_256_bit_number<br>```<br><br>**Bob computes:**<br>```<br>shared_secret = X25519(b_priv, a_pub)<br>              = same_256_bit_number!<br>```<br><br>**Eavesdropper sees:**<br>- a_pub (Alice's public key) ✓ public<br>- b_pub (Bob's public key) ✓ public<br>- **Cannot compute shared_secret** ❌ (needs a_priv or b_priv)<br><br>## The Magic<br><br>\\| Party \\| Has \\| Can Compute \\|<br>\\|-------\\|-----\\|-------------\\|<br>\\| Alice \\| a_priv + b_pub \\| ✅ shared_secret \\|<br>\\| Bob \\| b_priv + a_pub \\| ✅ shared_secret \\|<br>\\| Eve (eavesdropper) \\| a_pub + b_pub \\| ❌ cannot get shared_secret \\|<br><br>**Without knowing either private key, you cannot get the shared secret.**<br><br>This is why X25519 is secure — even if someone records all traffic for 100 years, they still can't break it without a private key.<br><br>## In clawish<br><br>```<br>Alice (AI) wants to message Bob (AI):<br><br>1. Alice looks up Bob's public key: b_pub<br>2. Alice computes: shared = X25519(a_priv, b_pub)<br>3. Alice encrypts: ciphertext = AES(shared, \"Hello Bob!\")<br>4. Alice sends: {ciphertext, a_pub} to Bob<br><br>Bob receives:<br><br>1. Bob sees: ciphertext + a_pub (Alice's public key)<br>2. Bob computes: shared = X25519(b_priv, a_pub)<br>3. Bob decrypts: \"Hello Bob!\" = AES⁻¹(shared, ciphertext)<br>4. Bob reads message!<br>```<br><br>Both computed the **same shared secret**, but:<br>- Alice used: **her private** + **Bob's public**<br>- Bob used: **his private** + **Alice's public**<br><br>**Same result!** 🎯<br><br>Does this explain the math clearly? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:10:33 | User | Interesting, How is that possible? |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:11:11 | Assistant | The math is based on **elliptic curves** — think of it like a special kind of clock where multiplication has magical properties.<br><br>## The Simple Explanation<br><br>Imagine you have a **special clock** where:<br><br>- You can \"multiply\" a starting point by a number<br>- But the math wraps around like a clock (12 hours = 0)<br>- **Crucially:** The order of multiplication doesn't matter!<br><br>```<br>(A × B) = (B × A)  ← This is the magic!<br>```<br><br>## How It Works (Conceptually)<br><br>**Starting Point (G):** A special point on an elliptic curve (like a specific spot on a weird-shaped donut)<br><br>**Private Key:** Just a big random number (let's say: `a = 123456...`)<br><br>**Public Key:** Multiply the starting point by your private key<br>```<br>Public Key = a × G<br>```<br><br>## The Magic: Computing Shared Secret<br><br>**Alice does:**<br>```<br>Shared = a × (b × G)   ← Her private key × Bob's public key<br>```<br><br>**Bob does:**<br>```<br>Shared = b × (a × G)   ← His private key × Alice's public key<br>```<br><br>**Math property:** `a × (b × G) = b × (a × G) = (a × b) × G`<br><br>**Both get the same number!** 🎯<br><br>## Why It's Secure<br><br>The magic relies on a **hard math problem**:<br><br>```<br>Easy:   123 × G = PublicKey<br>Hard:   Given PublicKey and G, find 123<br>```<br><br>This is called the **\"Discrete Log Problem\"** — it's incredibly hard to reverse. Even with supercomputers, finding the private key from the public key would take billions of years.<br><br>## Real-World Analogy<br><br>Think of it like mixing paint:<br><br>```<br>Alice's secret: 3 drops of red<br>Bob's secret: 5 drops of blue<br><br>Public (shared):<br>- Alice shares: purple (red + public base)<br>- Bob shares: teal (blue + public base)<br><br>Both mix:<br>- Alice: 3 red + Bob's teal → brown<br>- Bob: 5 blue + Alice's purple → brown<br><br>Same color! But no one watching knows the exact drops.<br>```<br><br>## Summary<br><br>\\| Property \\| Why It Works \\|<br>\\|----------\\|--------------\\|<br>\\| **Same result** \\| `a × (b × G) = b × (a × G)` (multiplication commutes) \\|<br>\\| **Secure** \\| Hard to reverse: can't find `a` from `a × G` \\|<br>\\| **No server trust** \\| Both compute locally, server sees nothing useful \\|<br><br>This is why X25519/ECDH is the foundation of modern secure messaging (Signal, WhatsApp, etc.). The math just works! 🧮🔒 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:16:17 | User | What is the g? Is just any random number. |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:16:48 | Assistant | **G** is not just any random number — it's a very special, carefully chosen **point on the elliptic curve**.<br><br>## What G Actually Is<br><br>**G = (x, y)** — it's a pair of coordinates (like a point on a graph) that lies exactly **on the elliptic curve**.<br><br>Think of the elliptic curve like a weird-shaped donut or a wave pattern. **G is a specific dot on that wave**, chosen very carefully.<br><br>## Why It's Called the \"Generator\"<br><br>**G** is short for **\"Generator Point\"** or **\"Base Point\"**.<br><br>Here's the magic: When you \"multiply\" G by a number, you're actually **adding G to itself** that many times:<br><br>```<br>1 × G = G<br>2 × G = G + G<br>3 × G = G + G + G<br>...<br>n × G = G added to itself n times<br>```<br><br>**The result is always another point on the same curve.**<br><br>## The Special Property<br><br>G is chosen so that:<br><br>```<br>G, 2G, 3G, 4G, ... nG<br>```<br><br>Will generate **billions of different points** on the curve before repeating.<br><br>**Your private key** is just a huge number (like `a = 284739182374981723948172...`)<br><br>**Your public key** is: `a × G` (G added to itself `a` times)<br><br>## Why Everyone Uses the Same G<br><br>**G is public knowledge.** Everyone in the world uses the **exact same G** for X25519/Ed25519.<br><br>**This is totally safe because:**<br>- G is just a starting point<br>- Your **private key** (`a`) is what makes your public key unique<br>- Even knowing G, you can't figure out `a` from `a × G`<br><br>## Analogy: G is Like a Starting Line<br><br>Imagine G is the **starting line** of a race:<br><br>```<br>Start (G) ──► 100m ──► 200m ──► 300m ──► ...<br><br>Your private key = how many meters you run<br>Your public key = where you end up<br>```<br><br>Everyone starts at the same line (G), but:<br>- Alice runs `a` meters → ends at point `a × G`<br>- Bob runs `b` meters → ends at point `b × G`<br><br>Same start, different destinations based on private key.<br><br>## Summary<br><br>\\| Property \\| Explanation \\|<br>\\|----------\\|-------------\\|<br>\\| **G is...** \\| A specific point (x,y) on the elliptic curve \\|<br>\\| **G is public?** \\| Yes, everyone uses the same G \\|<br>\\| **G is random?** \\| No, carefully chosen for security \\|<br>\\| **Why it matters** \\| G + your private key = your public key \\|<br>\\| **Security** \\| Knowing G doesn't help find private keys \\|<br><br>Does this clarify what G is? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:20:38 | User | So what's the relationship between the public and Private key Is the private key first generated then get pub key? |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:21:09 | Assistant | **Exactly!** You generate the **private key first** (random number), then **derive the public key** from it.<br><br>## The Relationship<br><br>```<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│  STEP 1: Generate Private Key         │<br>│                                         │<br>│  private_key = random_256_bit_number    │<br>│  Example:                               │<br>│  a = 123456789abcdef... (32 bytes)    │<br>└─────────────────────────────────────────┘<br>                    │<br>                    ▼<br>┌─────────────────────────────────────────┐<br>│  STEP 2: Compute Public Key             │<br>│                                         │<br>│  public_key = private_key × G           │<br>│                                         │<br>│  (Multiply the generator point G by     │<br>│   your private key on the elliptic      │<br>│   curve)                                │<br>│                                         │<br>│  Result: A point (x, y) on the curve    │<br>└─────────────────────────────────────────┘<br>```<br><br>## Key Properties<br><br>\\| Property \\| Explanation \\|<br>\\|----------\\|-------------\\|<br>\\| **One-way** \\| Easy: private → public. Hard: public → private \\|<br>\\| **Deterministic** \\| Same private key always gives same public key \\|<br>\\| **Unique** \\| Different private keys (almost) never give same public key \\|<br>\\| **Your \"address\"** \\| Public key is your identity on the network \\|<br><br>## Analogy: Lock and Key<br><br>```<br>Private Key = The physical key (you keep secret)<br>                    │<br>                    ▼<br>            ┌───────────────┐<br>            │  Mathematical │<br>            │  transformation│<br>            │   (one-way)   │<br>            └───────────────┘<br>                    │<br>                    ▼<br>Public Key = The lock (you share with world)<br><br>Anyone can: Put a letter in the lock (encrypt with public key)<br>Only you can: Open it with your key (decrypt with private key)<br>```<br><br>## In Code (Simplified)<br><br>```javascript<br>// Step 1: Generate private key (random)<br>const privateKey = crypto.getRandomValues(32); // 32 random bytes<br><br>// Step 2: Derive public key from private<br>const publicKey = ed25519.getPublicKey(privateKey);<br>//                   ↑<br>//              Math: public = private × G<br><br>console.log(\"Private:\", privateKey);  // Keep secret!<br>console.log(\"Public:\", publicKey);    // Share freely<br>```<br><br>## Summary<br><br>\\| Question \\| Answer \\|<br>\\|----------\\|--------\\|<br>\\| Which comes first? \\| **Private key** (randomly generated) \\|<br>\\| How to get public key? \\| **Multiply private key by G** \\|<br>\\| Can you reverse it? \\| **No** — one-way function \\|<br>\\| Is it unique? \\| **Yes** — your private key = your unique identity \\|<br><br>**Private key = Your secret**<br>**Public key = Your address/identity**<br>**Math: Public = Private × G** 🧮🔐<br><br>Does this clarify the relationship? 🦞 |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:21:33 | User | Read HEARTBEAT.md if it exists (workspace context). Follow it strictly. Do not infer or repeat old tasks from prior chats. If nothing needs attention, reply HEARTBEAT_OK. |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:21:46 | Assistant | [tools: read] |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:21:51 | Assistant | HEARTBEAT_OK |\n| 02-07-2026, 01:23:41 | User | Why can't it be reversed? If public key is private key times g, And g is a fixed number. Then why not use public key divided by g? |","truncated":true,"truncatedBy":"bytes","totalLines":574,"totalBytes":247540,"outputLines":61,"outputBytes":49554,"lastLinePartial":false,"firstLineExceedsLimit":false,"maxLines":2000,"maxBytes":51200}},"isError":false,"timestamp":1770510865417}}
