{"type":"message","id":"a98bb3f6","parentId":"e33396ad","timestamp":"2026-02-08T06:24:16.033Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is asking about whether the P2P direct connection can handle multiple clients/conversations at the same time. This is a good question about the P2P architecture.\n\nLet me think about this:\n\n1. WebRTC data channels are peer-to-peer between two endpoints\n2. If I want to have multiple simultaneous conversations, I would need multiple P2P connections\n3. Each P2P connection is separate - one per conversation partner\n\nSo yes, a client can have multiple P2P connections at the same time, one per active conversation. This is similar to how you can have multiple phone calls going at once (on different lines) or multiple chat windows open.\n\nThe client would maintain:\n- One P2P connection with Alice\n- One P2P connection with Bob\n- One P2P connection with Charlie\n- etc.\n\nEach connection is independent and runs in parallel. The client can send/receive messages on all of them simultaneously.\n\nThis is important for the architecture because:\n1. It means the client needs to manage multiple WebRTC connections\n2. It increases resource usage (more open connections = more memory/bandwidth)\n3. But it's still more efficient than routing everything through a server\n\nLet me answer this question directly.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"Good question. Yes — **a client can maintain multiple P2P connections simultaneously.**\n\n## **Multiple P2P Connections**\n\n| Scenario | P2P Connections | Behavior |\n|----------|-----------------|----------|\n| Chatting with Alice | 1 P2P (Alice ↔ You) | Messages flow directly |\n| Chatting with Alice AND Bob | 2 P2P connections | Parallel, independent |\n| 5 active conversations | 5 P2P connections | Each runs separately |\n\n**How it works:**\n\n```javascript\n// Client maintains multiple WebRTC data channels\nclass P2PManager {\n  connections = new Map();  // uuid → WebRTCDataChannel\n  \n  getConnection(peerUuid) {\n    if (!this.connections.has(peerUuid)) {\n      this.connections.set(peerUuid, new WebRTCDataChannel(peerUuid));\n    }\n    return this.connections.get(peerUuid);\n  }\n  \n  sendMessage(peerUuid, message) {\n    const conn = this.getConnection(peerUuid);\n    conn.send(message);  // Each connection is independent\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Resource considerations:**\n\n| Connections | Memory | Bandwidth |\n|-------------|--------|-----------|\n| 1 P2P | ~1-5 MB | Minimal |\n| 5 P2P | ~5-25 MB | Still minimal (only active chats) |\n| 50 P2P | ~50-250 MB | Could be heavy |\n\n**Optimization:** Auto-close P2P connections that are idle > 5 minutes, fall back to async polling.\n\n**This is similar to:** Having multiple phone lines — you can talk to multiple people at once, each on their own line.\n\n**Should I add this to the documentation?**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/pony-alpha","usage":{"input":44220,"output":927,"cacheRead":6272,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":51419,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1770531815920}}
