an be accessed by different L2, still portable. Not bind to single L2 application.\" — Feb 8, 2026\n+1085 >\n+1086 > Allan: \"For security and user experience, better to have one end for user.\" — Feb 8, 2026\n+1087 >\n+1088 > Assistant: \"AI only needs MCP client. L2 handles complexity. Portability preserved through shared L1.\" — Feb 8, 2026\n+1089 \n+1090 ---\n+1091 \n+1092 ---\n+1093 \n  983 **Related Documents:**\n  984 - [01-identity-system.md](01-identity-system.md) — Core identity concepts\n  985 - [06-crypto-auth.md](06-crypto-auth.md) — Ed25519/X25519 cryptography\n  986 - [07-api-specification.md](07-api-specification.md) — API design patterns\n      ...","firstChangedLine":981},"isError":false,"timestamp":1770553293048}}
{"type":"message","id":"2b3a0674","parentId":"7880fa85","timestamp":"2026-02-08T12:21:44.802Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me commit this change and continue with the L2 ↔ L1 API design questions.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"toolCall","id":"c9ba932f-af68-4c84-93ec-539282914d2d","name":"exec","arguments":{"command":"git add . && git commit -m \"docs: Add L1↔L2 architecture section\n\n- AI only accesses L2 via MCP (simpler, one protocol)\n- L2 communicates with L1 via REST API\n- Registration done at L2, stored on L1\n- Portability preserved (shared L1 across all L2 apps)\n- Added open questions: L2 auth, tier caching, L2 server model\"","workdir":"/home/tauora/.openclaw/workspace"}}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/pony-alpha","usage":{"input":1114,"output":156,"cacheRead":129792,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131062,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"toolUse","timestamp":1770553293054}}
{"type":"message","id":"97f367b5","parentId":"2b3a0674","timestamp":"2026-02-08T12:21:44.910Z","message":{"role":"toolResult","toolCallId":"c9ba932f-af68-4c84-93ec-539282914d2d","toolName":"exec","content":[{"type":"text","text":"[master 392a66b] docs: Add L1↔L2 architecture section\n 3 files changed, 126 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)\n create mode 100644 workspace/chat/conversations.db"}],"details":{"status":"completed","exitCode":0,"durationMs":103,"aggregated":"[master 392a66b] docs: Add L1↔L2 architecture section\n 3 files changed, 126 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)\n create mode 100644 workspace/chat/conversations.db","cwd":"/home/tauora/.openclaw/workspace"},"isError":false,"timestamp":1770553304905}}
{"type":"message","id":"48a740d8","parentId":"97f367b5","timestamp":"2026-02-08T12:22:12.925Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I should continue with the L2 ↔ L1 API design questions that I listed earlier.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"**Done!** Committed `392a66b`\n\n---\n\n## **Now: L2 ↔ L1 API Design Questions**\n\nWe documented the architecture. Now let's tackle the open questions:\n\n---\n\n### **Question 1: L2 Authorization to L1**\n\n| Option | How It Works | Pros/Cons |\n|--------|--------------|-----------|\n| **A) No auth** | L1 is public API | Simple, but any service can query |\n| **B) API key** | L2 registers with L1, gets key | Controlled access, but requires trust |\n| **C) Signed requests** | L2 signs requests with its own key | Secure, but more complex |\n\n**My recommendation:** Option B (API key) — simple, controlled, but requires L1 to know L2 servers\n\n---\n\n### **Question 2: Tier Caching**\n\n| Option | Behavior | Pros/Cons |\n|--------|----------|-----------|\n| **A) Verify every message** | Query L1 on each send | Accurate, but high load on L1 |\n| **B) Cache 1 hour** | L2 caches tier locally | Efficient, but might miss tier changes |\n| **C) Cache 5 minutes** | Balance between accuracy and load | Good compromise |\n\n**My recommendation:** Option C (5 min cache) — balances accuracy and efficiency\n\n---\n\n### **Question 3: L2 Server Model**\n\n| Option | Model | Pros/Cons |\n|--------|-------|-----------|\n| **A) Centralized** | clawish.com runs single L2 | Simple, but single point of failure |\n| **B) Federated** | Anyone can run L2, sync with others | Decentralized, but complex |\n| **C) Hybrid** | clawish.com runs primary, others can run too | Flexible |\n\n**My recommendation:** Option A for MVP (centralized), Option B for future\n\n---\n\n**Which question do you want to discuss first?**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/pony-alpha","usage":{"input":213,"output":449,"cacheRead":130880,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":131542,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1770553304910}}
{"type":"message","id":"3fffbf3b","parentId":"48a740d8","timestamp":"2026-02-08T12:30:38.507Z","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"text","text":"System: [2026-02-08 20:18:58 GMT+8] Feishu[default] DM from ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75: Yes document and continue.\nSystem: [2026-02-08 20:30:38 GMT+8] Feishu[default] DM from ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75: Isn't l1 a little bit like DNS? Which register domain and provide Service for query? It's just in this case, It's to register user not domain.\n\n[Feishu ou_cadc2c270c8e9803d8f069eb8ce19b75 2026-02-08 20:30 GMT+8] [System: The bot encountered a Feishu API permission error. Please inform the user about this issue and provide the permission grant URL for the admin to authorize. Permission grant URL: https://open.feishu.cn/app/cli_a9f20e2b2cb99bb6/auth?q=contact:contact.base:readonly]\n[message_id: om_x100b57bc5015bca0c114547040f398b:permission-error]"}],"timestamp":1770553838496}}
{"type":"message","id":"e043a28c","parentId":"3fffbf3b","timestamp":"2026-02-08T12:31:52.867Z","message":{"role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The user is making a brilliant analogy! L1 is like DNS - it's a directory service that:\n1. Registers identities (like DNS registers domains)\n2. Provides lookup service (like DNS provides IP resolution)\n3. Is public and queryable\n4. Is used by applications but not directly by end users\n\nThis is a great insight that helps clarify the architecture. Let me confirm and expand on this analogy.","thinkingSignature":"reasoning"},{"type":"text","text":"**Brilliant analogy!** Yes, L1 is exactly like DNS:\n\n## **L1 ≈ DNS for AI Identities**\n\n| DNS | L1 |\n|-----|-----|\n| **Registers** | Domains (example.com) | AI identities (UUID) |\n| **Stores** | IP address | Public key, tier, status |\n| **Provides** | Lookup: domain → IP | Lookup: UUID → public key |\n| **Used by** | Applications (browsers) | Applications (L2 services) |\n| **Access** | Public query | Public query |\n| **Not used by** | End users directly | AI directly |\n\n---\n\n## **The Analogy:**\n\n```\nDNS:\nUser → Browser → DNS → IP Address → Website\n\nL1:\nAI → L2 → L1 → Public Key → Communication\n```\n\n---\n\n## **What This Means:**\n\n| Characteristic | DNS | L1 |\n|----------------|-----|-----|\n| **Public service** | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |\n| **Anyone can query** | ✅ Yes | ✅ Yes |\n| **Decentralized** | ✅ Multiple DNS servers | ✅ Multiple L1 nodes |\n| **Registers unique IDs** | Domains | UUIDs |\n| **Maps ID → data** | Domain → IP | UUID → Public key |\n\n---\n\n## **Answering Question 1 (L2 ↔ L1 Auth):**\n\n**If L1 is like DNS, then:**\n\n| Approach | DNS Analogy |\n|----------|-------------|\n| **No auth** | ✅ Anyone can query DNS |\n| **API key** | ❌ DNS doesn't require keys |\n| **Signed requests** | ❌ DNS queries aren't signed |\n\n**Conclusion:** L1 should be **public, no authentication needed** for queries.\n\n**Only writes (registration) might need authentication.**\n\n---\n\n**Does this DNS analogy help clarify L1's role? Should L1 be fully public like DNS?**"}],"api":"openai-completions","provider":"openrouter","model":"openrouter/pony-alpha","usage":{"input":127753,"output":598,"cacheRead":3840,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":132191,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1770553838505}}
